n of large amounts. These adverse reactions can occur due to the plant's high thymol content, which can cause gastrointestinal issues and skin irritation in some individuals. The improper use of Thymus bracteatus var. penyalarensis can also lead to allergic reactions, especially in people with pre-existing allergies. Individuals with sensitive skin or respiratory issues should exercise caution when handling this plant to avoid potential side effects. Ingesting large amounts of Thymus bracteatus var. penyalarensis can lead to severe nausea, vomiting, and other gastrointestinal issues.", "family_slug": "lamiaceae", "family_name": "Lamiaceae", "what_description": "Thymus bracteatus var. penyalarensis is a variety of the plant species Thymus bracteatus within the genus Thymus, belonging to the family Lamiaceae. It is characterized by its woody stems, often growing up to 30 cm in height, and its elliptical, serrated leaves, measuring 5-15 mm in length, which are dark green in color. The leaves are arranged oppositely on the stem, and the plant produces small, tubular flowers in shades of pink, purple, and white, which are clustered in axillary whorls. The flowers are 8-12 mm in length, with a calyx of 4-5 mm and a corolla of 6-8 mm, and are produced in the summer months. Thymus bracteatus var. penyalarensis is native to the Iberian Peninsula, specifically in the region of Aragon, Spain."}